Category COUNTS

category counts total

# Step 1: Select the columns that end with "_comp"
comp_columns <- comparison_data_processed %>%
  select(ends_with("_comp"))

# Step 2: Get the number of columns (items/categories)
num_columns <- ncol(comp_columns)

# Step 3: Get the number of unique psps (rows)
num_psps <- nrow(comparison_data_processed)

# Step 4: Create a new dataset that counts the occurrences of each category across all "_comp" columns
data_category_counts_total <- comp_columns %>%
  summarise(
    Identical_YES = sum(comp_columns == "Y", na.rm = TRUE),
    Identical_NO = sum(comp_columns == "N", na.rm = TRUE),
    Identical_X = sum(comp_columns == "X", na.rm = TRUE),
    Different_Y_to_N = sum(comp_columns == "P", na.rm = TRUE),
    Different_N_to_Y = sum(comp_columns == "Q", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_Y_Olmo_X = sum(comp_columns == "FY", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_N_Olmo_X = sum(comp_columns == "FN", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_X_Olmo_N = sum(comp_columns == "FXN", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_X_Olmo_Y = sum(comp_columns == "FXY", na.rm = TRUE),
    n_answers_total = sum(
      comp_columns == "Y" | comp_columns == "N" | comp_columns == "X" |
      comp_columns == "P" | comp_columns == "Q" | comp_columns == "FY" |
      comp_columns == "FN" | comp_columns == "FXN" | comp_columns == "FXY", na.rm = TRUE
    )
  )

# Step 5: Add percentages as a second row
data_category_counts_percent <- data_category_counts_total %>%
  mutate(across(-n_answers_total, ~ round((.x / data_category_counts_total$n_answers_total) * 100, 2))) %>%
  mutate(n_answers_total = 100)

# Step 6: Combine the two with row labels
data_category_counts_total <- rbind(
  cbind(type = "counts_total_absolute", data_category_counts_total),
  cbind(type = "counts_total_percent", data_category_counts_percent)
)

# Step 7: Print the combined table with both counts and percentages
print(data_category_counts_total)

3x3 confusionsmatrix absolut

# Extrahiere nur die relevanten Werte fr Y, N, X (jeweils fr tatschliche und vorhergesagte Werte)
actual_Y <- data_category_counts_total$Identical_YES[1]  # Zhle die Y-Zuordnungen
actual_N <- data_category_counts_total$Identical_NO[1]   # Zhle die N-Zuordnungen
actual_X <- data_category_counts_total$Identical_X[1]    # Zhle die X-Zuordnungen

pred_Y_to_N <- data_category_counts_total$Different_Y_to_N[1]  # Y -> N Zhlungen
pred_N_to_Y <- data_category_counts_total$Different_N_to_Y[1]  # N -> Y Zhlungen
pred_Y_to_X <- data_category_counts_total$GPT_Y_Olmo_X[1]      # Y -> X Zhlungen
pred_N_to_X <- data_category_counts_total$GPT_N_Olmo_X[1]      # N -> X Zhlungen
pred_X_to_N <- data_category_counts_total$GPT_X_Olmo_N[1]      # X -> N Zhlungen
pred_X_to_Y <- data_category_counts_total$GPT_X_Olmo_Y[1]      # X -> Y Zhlungen

# Erstelle eine leere 3x3-Matrix
confusion_matrix <- matrix(0, nrow = 3, ncol = 3, 
                           dimnames = list(c("Actual_Y", "Actual_N", "Actual_X"), 
                                           c("Predicted_Y", "Predicted_N", "Predicted_X")))

# Flle die Konfusionsmatrix basierend auf den Zhlungen aus
confusion_matrix["Actual_Y", "Predicted_Y"] <- actual_Y
confusion_matrix["Actual_N", "Predicted_N"] <- actual_N
confusion_matrix["Actual_X", "Predicted_X"] <- actual_X

# Fge die 'False Positives' und 'False Negatives' hinzu
confusion_matrix["Actual_Y", "Predicted_N"] <- pred_Y_to_N
confusion_matrix["Actual_N", "Predicted_Y"] <- pred_N_to_Y
confusion_matrix["Actual_Y", "Predicted_X"] <- pred_Y_to_X
confusion_matrix["Actual_X", "Predicted_Y"] <- pred_X_to_Y
confusion_matrix["Actual_N", "Predicted_X"] <- pred_N_to_X
confusion_matrix["Actual_X", "Predicted_N"] <- pred_X_to_N

# Ausgabe der 3x3 Konfusionsmatrix
print(confusion_matrix)
##          Predicted_Y Predicted_N Predicted_X
## Actual_Y        7177        5224        7256
## Actual_N         382        1106        2172
## Actual_X         938         534       11673

# Berechnung der Summe der Zeilen und Spalten
row_sums <- rowSums(confusion_matrix)  # Summe ber die Zeilen (horizontal)
col_sums <- colSums(confusion_matrix)  # Summe ber die Spalten (vertikal)
n_total <- sum(confusion_matrix)       # Gesamtsumme

# Erstelle eine erweiterte Konfusionsmatrix, die Zeilen- und Spaltensummen enthlt
confusion_matrix_with_sums <- rbind(confusion_matrix, "Sum" = col_sums)  # Spaltensummen als neue Zeile hinzufgen
confusion_matrix_with_sums <- cbind(confusion_matrix_with_sums, "Sum" = c(row_sums, n_total))  # Zeilensummen und Gesamtsumme hinzufgen

# Ergebnis als Matrix anzeigen, um alle Summen zu berprfen

category counts per item

# Step 1: Select the columns that end with "_comp"
comp_columns <- comparison_data_processed %>%
  select(ends_with("_comp"))

# Step 2: Create a dataset that counts occurrences of each category for each column using reframe()
data_category_counts_per_item <- comp_columns %>%
  reframe(across(everything(), ~ tibble(
    Identical_YES = sum(. == "Y", na.rm = TRUE),
    Identical_NO = sum(. == "N", na.rm = TRUE),
    Identical_X = sum(. == "X", na.rm = TRUE),
    Different_Y_to_N = sum(. == "P", na.rm = TRUE),
    Different_N_to_Y = sum(. == "Q", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_Y_Olmo_X = sum(. == "FY", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_N_Olmo_X = sum(. == "FN", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_X_Olmo_N = sum(. == "FXN", na.rm = TRUE),
    GPT_X_Olmo_Y = sum(. == "FXY", na.rm = TRUE)
  )))

# Step 3: Transpose the data so that each category has its own column
data_category_counts_per_item <- data_category_counts_per_item %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "Column", values_to = "Counts") %>%
  unnest_wider(Counts)

# Step 4: Print the result
print(data_category_counts_per_item)

Quality MEASURES

Sensitivitt und Spezifitt und accuracy fr jede Klasse (One-vs-Rest)

print(confusion_matrix)
##          Predicted_Y Predicted_N Predicted_X
## Actual_Y        7177        5224        7256
## Actual_N         382        1106        2172
## Actual_X         938         534       11673
n_total <- sum(confusion_matrix)
# Berechnung der Sensitivitt, Spezifitt und Przision fr jede Klasse
# Y-Klasse
TP_Y <- confusion_matrix['Actual_Y', 'Predicted_Y']
FN_Y <- sum(confusion_matrix['Actual_Y', ]) - TP_Y
FP_Y <- sum(confusion_matrix[, 'Predicted_Y']) - TP_Y
TN_Y <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TP_Y + FN_Y + FP_Y)
sensitivity_Y <- TP_Y / (TP_Y + FN_Y)
specificity_Y <- TN_Y / (TN_Y + FP_Y)
precision_Y <- TP_Y / (TP_Y + FP_Y)
# N-Klasse
TP_N <- confusion_matrix['Actual_N', 'Predicted_N']
FN_N <- sum(confusion_matrix['Actual_N', ]) - TP_N
FP_N <- sum(confusion_matrix[, 'Predicted_N']) - TP_N
TN_N <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TP_N + FN_N + FP_N)
sensitivity_N <- TP_N / (TP_N + FN_N)
specificity_N <- TN_N / (TN_N + FP_N)
precision_N <- TP_N / (TP_N + FP_N)
# X-Klasse
TP_X <- confusion_matrix['Actual_X', 'Predicted_X']
FN_X <- sum(confusion_matrix['Actual_X', ]) - TP_X
FP_X <- sum(confusion_matrix[, 'Predicted_X']) - TP_X
TN_X <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TP_X + FN_X + FP_X)
sensitivity_X <- TP_X / (TP_X + FN_X)
specificity_X <- TN_X / (TN_X + FP_X)
precision_X <- TP_X / (TP_X + FP_X)

# Funktion zur Berechnung des Wilson-Konfidenzintervalls
wilson_ci <- function(successes, total, conf_level = 0.95) {
  z <- qnorm(1 - (1 - conf_level) / 2)
  phat <- successes / total
  denominator <- 1 + (z^2 / total)
  center <- phat + (z^2 / (2 * total))
  margin <- z * sqrt((phat * (1 - phat) + (z^2 / (4 * total))) / total)
  
  lower <- (center - margin) / denominator
  upper <- (center + margin) / denominator
  
  return(c(lower = lower, upper = upper))
}

# Berechnung der Konfidenzintervalle fr die Y-Klasse
ci_sensitivity_Y <- wilson_ci(TP_Y, TP_Y + FN_Y)
ci_specificity_Y <- wilson_ci(TN_Y, TN_Y + FP_Y)
ci_precision_Y <- wilson_ci(TP_Y, TP_Y + FP_Y)

# Berechnung der Konfidenzintervalle fr die N-Klasse
ci_sensitivity_N <- wilson_ci(TP_N, TP_N + FN_N)
ci_specificity_N <- wilson_ci(TN_N, TN_N + FP_N)
ci_precision_N <- wilson_ci(TP_N, TP_N + FP_N)

# Berechnung der Konfidenzintervalle fr die X-Klasse
ci_sensitivity_X <- wilson_ci(TP_X, TP_X + FN_X)
ci_specificity_X <- wilson_ci(TN_X, TN_X + FP_X)
ci_precision_X <- wilson_ci(TP_X, TP_X + FP_X)

# Ergebnisse in einer Tabelle mit Konfidenzintervallen anzeigen
results_with_ci <- data.frame(
  Class = c("Y", "N", "X"),
  Sensitivity = round(c(sensitivity_Y, sensitivity_N, sensitivity_X), 2),
  Sensitivity_CI = paste0("[", round(c(ci_sensitivity_Y[1], ci_sensitivity_N[1], ci_sensitivity_X[1]), 2), 
                          ", ", round(c(ci_sensitivity_Y[2], ci_sensitivity_N[2], ci_sensitivity_X[2]), 2), "]"),
  Specificity = round(c(specificity_Y, specificity_N, specificity_X), 2),
  Specificity_CI = paste0("[", round(c(ci_specificity_Y[1], ci_specificity_N[1], ci_specificity_X[1]), 2), 
                          ", ", round(c(ci_specificity_Y[2], ci_specificity_N[2], ci_specificity_X[2]), 2), "]"),
  Precision = round(c(precision_Y, precision_N, precision_X), 2),
  Precision_CI = paste0("[", round(c(ci_precision_Y[1], ci_precision_N[1], ci_precision_X[1]), 2), 
                        ", ", round(c(ci_precision_Y[2], ci_precision_N[2], ci_precision_X[2]), 2), "]")
)

print(results_with_ci)

##   Precision_CI
## 1 [0.84, 0.85]
## 2 [0.15, 0.17]
## 3 [0.55, 0.56]

Sensitivity (Sensitivitt) gibt an, wie gut das Modell positive Flle (z.B. Y) korrekt erkennt. Es ist das Verhltnis von richtig-positiven Vorhersagen zu allen tatschlichen positiven Fllen. Hhere Werte zeigen eine bessere Erkennungsrate der positiven Flle.

Specificity (Spezifitt) gibt an, wie gut das Modell negative Flle (z.B. Nicht-Y) korrekt erkennt. Es ist das Verhltnis von richtig-negativen Vorhersagen zu allen tatschlichen negativen Fllen. Hhere Werte bedeuten, dass das Modell weniger falsch-positive Vorhersagen macht.

Precision (Przision) gibt an, wie viele der als positiv (z.B. Y) vorhergesagten Flle tatschlich positiv sind. Es ist das Verhltnis von richtig-positiven Vorhersagen zu allen positiven Vorhersagen. Hohe Przision bedeutet, dass das Modell selten falsch-positive Vorhersagen macht.

Gesamtleistung: Macro- und Micro-Averaging

## Berechnung von Macro-Averaging (Mittelwert der Sensitivitten, Spezifitten und Przisionen)
macro_sensitivity <- mean(c(sensitivity_Y, sensitivity_N, sensitivity_X))
macro_specificity <- mean(c(specificity_Y, specificity_N, specificity_X))
macro_precision <- mean(c(precision_Y, precision_N, precision_X))

# Micro-Averaging (Summe der TP, FN, FP, TN ber alle Klassen)
TP_total <- TP_Y + TP_N + TP_X
FN_total <- FN_Y + FN_N + FN_X
FP_total <- FP_Y + FP_N + FP_X
TN_total <- TN_Y + TN_N + TN_X

micro_sensitivity <- TP_total / (TP_total + FN_total)
micro_specificity <- TN_total / (TN_total + FP_total)
micro_precision <- TP_total / (TP_total + FP_total)



# Berechnung der Accuracy (Genauigkeit)s
accuracy1 <- (TP_total + TN_total) / (TP_total + TN_total + FP_total + FN_total)

accuracy2 <- TP_total/(n_total)

balanced_accuracy <- (sensitivity_Y + sensitivity_N + sensitivity_X)/3

# Ergebnisse fr Macro, Micro und Accuracy anzeigen
overall_results <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Macro Sensitivity", "Macro Specificity", "Macro Precision",
             "Micro Sensitivity", "Micro Specificity", "Micro Precision",
            "accuracy1","accuracy2","balanced_accuracy"),
  Value = c(macro_sensitivity, macro_specificity, macro_precision,
            micro_sensitivity, micro_specificity, micro_precision,
            accuracy1,accuracy2,balanced_accuracy)
)

print(overall_results)

negative predictive value fr jede Klasse

print(confusion_matrix)
##          Predicted_Y Predicted_N Predicted_X
## Actual_Y        7177        5224        7256
## Actual_N         382        1106        2172
## Actual_X         938         534       11673
n_total <- sum(confusion_matrix)

#Berechnung des Wilson-Konfidenzintervalls
wilson_ci <- function(successes, total, conf_level = 0.95) {
  z <- qnorm(1 - (1 - conf_level) / 2)
  phat <- successes / total
  denominator <- 1 + (z^2 / total)
  center <- phat + (z^2 / (2 * total))
  margin <- z * sqrt((phat * (1 - phat) + (z^2 / (4 * total))) / total)
  
  lower <- (center - margin) / denominator
  upper <- (center + margin) / denominator
  
  return(c(lower = lower, upper = upper))
}

# Berechnung fr jede Klasse (Y, N, X)
calculate_metrics <- function(confusion_matrix, actual_class, predicted_class) {
  TP <- confusion_matrix[actual_class, predicted_class]
  FN <- sum(confusion_matrix[actual_class, ]) - TP
  FP <- sum(confusion_matrix[, predicted_class]) - TP
  TN <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TP + FN + FP)
  
  sensitivity <- TP / (TP + FN)
  specificity <- TN / (TN + FP)
  precision <- TP / (TP + FP)
  npv <- TN / (TN + FN) # Negative Predictive Value
  
  ci_sensitivity <- wilson_ci(TP, TP + FN)
  ci_specificity <- wilson_ci(TN, TN + FP)
  ci_precision <- wilson_ci(TP, TP + FP)
  ci_npv <- wilson_ci(TN, TN + FN)
  
  return(list(
    sensitivity = sensitivity,
    specificity = specificity,
    precision = precision,
    npv = npv,
    ci_sensitivity = ci_sensitivity,
    ci_specificity = ci_specificity,
    ci_precision = ci_precision,
    ci_npv = ci_npv
  ))
}

# Ergebnisse fr die Klassen berechnen
metrics_Y <- calculate_metrics(confusion_matrix, "Actual_Y", "Predicted_Y")
metrics_N <- calculate_metrics(confusion_matrix, "Actual_N", "Predicted_N")
metrics_X <- calculate_metrics(confusion_matrix, "Actual_X", "Predicted_X")

# Ergebnisse in einer Tabelle mit Konfidenzintervallen anzeigen
results_with_ci <- data.frame(
  Class = c("Y", "N", "X"),
  Sensitivity = round(c(metrics_Y$sensitivity, metrics_N$sensitivity, metrics_X$sensitivity), 2),
  Sensitivity_CI = paste0("[", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_sensitivity[1], metrics_N$ci_sensitivity[1], metrics_X$ci_sensitivity[1]), 2), 
                          ", ", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_sensitivity[2], metrics_N$ci_sensitivity[2], metrics_X$ci_sensitivity[2]), 2), "]"),
  Specificity = round(c(metrics_Y$specificity, metrics_N$specificity, metrics_X$specificity), 2),
  Specificity_CI = paste0("[", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_specificity[1], metrics_N$ci_specificity[1], metrics_X$ci_specificity[1]), 2), 
                          ", ", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_specificity[2], metrics_N$ci_specificity[2], metrics_X$ci_specificity[2]), 2), "]"),
  Precision = round(c(metrics_Y$precision, metrics_N$precision, metrics_X$precision), 2),
  Precision_CI = paste0("[", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_precision[1], metrics_N$ci_precision[1], metrics_X$ci_precision[1]), 2), 
                        ", ", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_precision[2], metrics_N$ci_precision[2], metrics_X$ci_precision[2]), 2), "]"),
  NPV = round(c(metrics_Y$npv, metrics_N$npv, metrics_X$npv), 2),
  NPV_CI = paste0("[", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_npv[1], metrics_N$ci_npv[1], metrics_X$ci_npv[1]), 2), 
                  ", ", round(c(metrics_Y$ci_npv[2], metrics_N$ci_npv[2], metrics_X$ci_npv[2]), 2), "]")
)

Kappa RETEST

test, retest korrelation Cohens Kappa per category v1

# Step 1: Filter the dataset into test and retest subsets
test_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "Test")
retest_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "RETEST")

# Step 2: Match test and retest based on 'psp'(so this only contains the 30 test-retst Psp rows)
retest_merged_data <- merge(test_data, retest_data, by = "psp", suffixes = c("_test", "_retest"))

# Step 3: Get all columns ending with '_comp'
comp_columns <- grep("_comp$", names(comparison_data_processed), value = TRUE)

# Step 4: Loop through each '_comp' column and calculate Cohen's Kappa
retest_kappa_results <- lapply(comp_columns, function(col_name) {
  # Cohen's Kappa requires the two sets of categorical data (Test and RETEST)
  test_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]]
  retest_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]]
  
  # Calculate Cohen's Kappa for the current column
  kappa <- cohen.kappa(cbind(test_col, retest_col))
  
  # Return the column name and the kappa value
  data.frame(Column = col_name, Kappa = kappa$kappa)
})

test, retest korrelation Cohens Kappa per category v2 mit zustzlich z wert, agreement % , p wert

# Step 1: Filter the dataset into test and retest subsets
test_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "Test")
retest_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "RETEST")

# Step 2: Match test and retest based on 'psp' (so this only contains the 30 test-retest psp rows)
retest_merged_data <- merge(test_data, retest_data, by = "psp", suffixes = c("_test", "_retest"))

# Step 3: Get all columns ending with '_comp'
comp_columns <- grep("_comp$", names(comparison_data_processed), value = TRUE)

# Step 4: Loop through each '_comp' column and calculate Cohen's Kappa using the irr package
retest_kappa_results <- lapply(comp_columns, function(col_name) {
  # Cohen's Kappa requires the two sets of categorical data (Test and RETEST)
  test_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]]
  retest_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]]
  
  # berprfung auf gltige Daten (Nicht-NA-Daten) in beiden Spalten
  if (all(is.na(test_col)) || all(is.na(retest_col))) {
    # Falls alle Daten NA sind, gib eine Zeile mit NA zurck
    return(data.frame(Column = col_name, Kappa = NA, z_value = NA, 
                      Agreement_Percentage = NA, p_value = NA))
  }
  
  # Berechnung von Cohen's Kappa mit dem irr-Paket
  kappa_result <- kappa2(data.frame(test_col, retest_col), "unweighted")
  
  # Extrahiere den Kappa-Wert und p-Wert
  kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
  p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
  agreement_percentage <- mean(test_col == retest_col, na.rm = TRUE) * 100
  
  # Berechnung der erwarteten bereinstimmung (p_e)
  test_table <- table(test_col, retest_col)
  n <- sum(test_table)  # Anzahl der Paare
  p_e <- sum(rowSums(test_table) * colSums(test_table)) / (n^2)
  
  # Berechnung der beobachteten bereinstimmung (p_0)
  p_0 <- agreement_percentage / 100
  
  # Berechnung des Standardfehlers (SE)
  if (p_e == 1) {
    se_kappa <- NA  # Vermeide Division durch 0, wenn p_e = 1 (perfekte bereinstimmung)
    z_value <- NA
  } else {
    se_kappa <- sqrt((p_0 * (1 - p_0)) / (n * (1 - p_e)^2))
  
    # Berechnung des z-Werts
    z_value <- kappa_value / se_kappa
  }
  
  # Return the column name, Kappa, z-value, agreement %, and p-value
  return(data.frame(Column = col_name, Kappa = kappa_value, z_value = z_value, 
                    Agreement_Percentage = agreement_percentage, p_value = p_value))
})

test, retest korrelation Cohens Kappa per category v3

# Step 1: Filter the dataset into test and retest subsets
test_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "Test")
retest_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "RETEST")

# Step 2: Merge test and retest data based on 'psp' to only include the 30 test-retest psp rows
retest_merged_data <- merge(test_data, retest_data, by = "psp", suffixes = c("_test", "_retest"))

# Step 3: Get all columns ending with '_comp'
comp_columns <- grep("_comp$", names(comparison_data_processed), value = TRUE)

# Step 4: Create a new dataframe to store the results
retest_kappa_summary_v3 <- data.frame(
  Variable = comp_columns,
  Kappa = NA,
  P_Value = NA,
  Z_Value = NA,
  Percent_Agreement = NA
)

# Step 5: Loop through each '_comp' column and calculate Cohen's Kappa without adjustments for high percent agreement
for (i in 1:length(comp_columns)) {
  col_name <- comp_columns[i]
  
  # Extract the test and retest columns for the current '_comp' item
  test_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]]
  retest_col <- retest_merged_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]]
  
  # Check if there are non-NA data in both columns
  if (!all(is.na(test_col)) && !all(is.na(retest_col))) {
    # Remove rows with NA values for this comparison
    valid_data <- retest_merged_data[!is.na(test_col) & !is.na(retest_col), ]
    
    # Calculate Cohen's Kappa using the 'irr' package without any special adjustments
    kappa_result <- irr::kappa2(data.frame(valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]], 
                                           valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]]), "unweighted")
    
    # Extract kappa value and p-value
    kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
    p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
    agreement_percentage <- mean(valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]] == 
                                 valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]]) * 100
    
    # Calculate expected agreement (p_e)
    agreement_table <- table(valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_test")]], valid_data[[paste0(col_name, "_retest")]])
    n <- sum(agreement_table)  # Total number of pairs
    p_e <- sum(rowSums(agreement_table) * colSums(agreement_table)) / (n^2)
    
    # Calculate observed agreement (p_0)
    p_0 <- agreement_percentage / 100
    
    # Calculate standard error (SE) and z-value if p_e < 1
    if (p_e < 1) {
      se_kappa <- sqrt((p_0 * (1 - p_0)) / (n * (1 - p_e)^2))
      z_value <- kappa_value / se_kappa
    } else {
      se_kappa <- NA
      z_value <- NA
    }
    
    # Store the results in the dataframe
    retest_kappa_summary_v3[i, ] <- c(col_name, kappa_value, p_value, z_value, agreement_percentage)
  }
}

average retest-kappa over items

# Berechnung des Durchschnitts der Spalte 'Kappa' und Rundung auf 2 Nachkommastellen
mean_kappa <- round(mean(retest_kappa_summary$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)

# Berechnung der Standardabweichung der Spalte 'Kappa' und Rundung auf 2 Nachkommastellen
sd_kappa <- round(sd(retest_kappa_summary$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)

# Berechnung des Bereichs (Range) der Spalte 'Kappa' und Rundung auf 2 Nachkommastellen
range_kappa <- round(range(retest_kappa_summary$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)

# Ausgabe der Ergebnisse
cat("Durchschnittlicher Kappa-Wert:", mean_kappa, "\n")
## Durchschnittlicher Kappa-Wert: 0.57
cat("Standardabweichung des Kappa-Werts:", sd_kappa, "\n")
## Standardabweichung des Kappa-Werts: 0.32
cat("Bereich des Kappa-Werts:", range_kappa[1], "-", range_kappa[2], "\n")
## Bereich des Kappa-Werts: -0.09 - 1

Ob der durchschnittliche Kappa-Wert (average Kappa) oder das Gesamtkappa grer ist, hngt von der Verteilung der bereinstimmungen und Nicht-bereinstimmungen innerhalb der einzelnen Items ab. Es gibt bestimmte Situationen, in denen der eine Wert grer ist als der andere, und das hngt von der Struktur der Daten ab.

weighted macht hier keinen sinn

##test, retest korrelation gesamt kappav2 mit p wert etc..

# Funktion zur Berechnung des 95%-Konfidenzintervalls fr Cohen's Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, se_kappa) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa)) {
    ci_lower <- kappa_value - 1.96 * se_kappa
    ci_upper <- kappa_value + 1.96 * se_kappa
    return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein CI, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Berechnung der erwarteten bereinstimmung (p_e)
test_table <- table(all_test_values, all_retest_values)
n <- sum(test_table)  # Anzahl der Paare
p_e <- sum(rowSums(test_table) * colSums(test_table)) / (n^2)

# Berechnung der beobachteten bereinstimmung (p_0)
p_0 <- agreement_percentage / 100

# Berechnung des Standardfehlers (SE)
if (p_e == 1) {
  se_kappa <- NA  # Vermeide Division durch 0, wenn p_e = 1 (perfekte bereinstimmung)
  z_value <- NA
} else {
  se_kappa <- sqrt((p_0 * (1 - p_0)) / (n * (1 - p_e)^2))
  
  # Berechnung des z-Werts
  z_value <- kappa_value / se_kappa
}

# Berechne das 95%-Konfidenzintervall fr Cohen's Kappa
ci_kappa <- calculate_kappa_confidence_interval(kappa_value, se_kappa)

# Schritt 6: Zeige das Gesamtergebnis an, einschlielich des Konfidenzintervalls
retest_kappa_all_summary <- data.frame(
  Kappa = kappa_value,
  Agreement_Percentage = agreement_percentage,
  z_value = z_value,
  p_value = p_value,
  CI_Lower = ci_kappa[1],
  CI_Upper = ci_kappa[2],
  n = n  # Anzahl der Beobachtungen
)

# Zeige das Gesamtergebnis an
print(retest_kappa_all_summary)
##       Kappa Agreement_Percentage  z_value      p_value  CI_Lower  CI_Upper    n
## 1 0.8345588                   90 130.1641 1.213182e-09 0.8219921 0.8471255 3540

# Step 1: Filter the dataset into test and retest subsets
test_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "Test")
retest_data <- comparison_data_processed %>% filter(test_retest == "RETEST")

# Step 2: Match test and retest based on 'psp' (so this only contains the 30 test-retest PSP rows)
retest_merged_data <- merge(test_data, retest_data, by = "psp", suffixes = c("_test", "_retest"))

# Step 3: Define columns for extraction and comparison
extract_columns <- grep("^(c_pre|pre|c_pap|pap).*_comp$", names(comparison_data_processed), value = TRUE)
comp_columns <- grep("^(c_match|match).*_comp$", names(comparison_data_processed), value = TRUE)

# Funktion zur Berechnung von Kappa nur fr ausgewhlte Spalten und Zeilen
calculate_kappa_for_selected <- function(columns, label_suffix) {
  # Berechnung fr die ausgewhlten Spalten (Extract oder Comparison)
  all_test_values <- unlist(retest_merged_data[paste0(columns, "_test")])
  all_retest_values <- unlist(retest_merged_data[paste0(columns, "_retest")])
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa fr die aktuellen Spalten und speichere die Ergebnisse
  kappa_result <- cohen.kappa(cbind(all_test_values, all_retest_values))
  data.frame(Category = label_suffix, Kappa = kappa_result$kappa)
}

# Berechnung fr Extraktions-Items
retest_kappa_extraction <- calculate_kappa_for_selected(extract_columns, "retest_extraction")

# Berechnung fr Vergleichs-Items
retest_kappa_comparison <- calculate_kappa_for_selected(comp_columns, "retest_comparison")

# Zusammenfassung der Ergebnisse
retest_kappa_extraction_comparison <- rbind(retest_kappa_extraction, retest_kappa_comparison)

# Ergebnisse anzeigen
print(retest_kappa_extraction_comparison)
##            Category     Kappa
## 1 retest_extraction 0.7091343
## 2 retest_comparison 0.7963016

#Kappa INTERRATER gpt zu olmo

Kappa interrater gpt zu olmo per ITEM/category

# Function to calculate Cohen's Kappa, p-value, z-value, and percentage agreement
calculate_kappa_stats <- function(data, column_gpt, column_olmo) {
  # Ensure both columns exist
  if(column_gpt %in% colnames(data) & column_olmo %in% colnames(data)) {
    # Calculate Cohen's Kappa
    kappa_result <- psych::cohen.kappa(cbind(data[[column_gpt]], data[[column_olmo]]))
    
    # Extract values
    kappa_value <- kappa_result$kappa
    p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
    z_value <- kappa_result$z
    percent_agreement <- sum(data[[column_gpt]] == data[[column_olmo]], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(data) * 100
    
    return(c(kappa_value, p_value, z_value, percent_agreement))
  } else {
    return(rep(NA, 4))
  }
}

# Get all columns that have _gpt or _olmo suffix
gpt_columns <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns)

# Create a dataframe to store the results
kappa_results <- data.frame(Variable = gpt_columns, Kappa = NA, P_Value = NA, Z_Value = NA, Percent_Agreement = NA)

# Loop over all _gpt and _olmo column pairs and calculate statistics
for(i in 1:length(gpt_columns)) {
  kappa_stats <- calculate_kappa_stats(data_gpt_olmo_processed, gpt_columns[i], olmo_columns[i])
  kappa_results[i, 2:5] <- kappa_stats
}


# Entfernen der Variablen pre_dcp_1_text_gpt und pap_dcp_1_text_gpt aus kappa_results, da diese numerische variablen sind...
kappa_results <- kappa_results[!(kappa_results$Variable %in% c("pre_dcp_1_text_gpt", "pap_dcp_1_text_gpt")), ]

##Kappa interrater gpt zu olmo per ITEM/Category 2. ansatz

# Function to calculate Cohen's Kappa, p-value, z-value, and percentage agreement using 'irr' package
calculate_kappa_irr_v2 <- function(data, column_gpt, column_olmo) {
  # Ensure both columns exist
  if(column_gpt %in% colnames(data) & column_olmo %in% colnames(data)) {
    # Remove rows with NA values to avoid errors in kappa calculation
    valid_data_v2 <- data[!is.na(data[[column_gpt]]) & !is.na(data[[column_olmo]]), ]
    
    # Calculate Cohen's Kappa using the 'kappa2' function from the irr package
    kappa_result_v2 <- irr::kappa2(valid_data_v2[, c(column_gpt, column_olmo)], "unweighted")
    
    # Extract values
    kappa_value_v2 <- kappa_result_v2$value
    p_value_v2 <- kappa_result_v2$p.value
    z_value_v2 <- kappa_result_v2$statistic
    percent_agreement_v2 <- sum(valid_data_v2[[column_gpt]] == valid_data_v2[[column_olmo]]) / nrow(valid_data_v2) * 100
    
    return(c(kappa_value_v2, p_value_v2, z_value_v2, percent_agreement_v2))
  } else {
    return(rep(NA, 4))
  }
}

# Get all columns that have _gpt or _olmo suffix
gpt_columns_v2 <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_v2 <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_v2)

# Create a dataframe to store the results
kappa_results_v2 <- data.frame(Variable = gpt_columns_v2, Kappa = NA, P_Value = NA, Z_Value = NA, Percent_Agreement = NA)

# Loop over all _gpt and _olmo column pairs and calculate statistics
for(i in 1:length(gpt_columns_v2)) {
  kappa_stats_v2 <- calculate_kappa_irr_v2(data_gpt_olmo_processed, gpt_columns_v2[i], olmo_columns_v2[i])
  kappa_results_v2[i, 2:5] <- kappa_stats_v2
}

##Kappa interrater gpt zu olmo per ITEM/Category 3. ansatz

# Function to calculate Cohen's Kappa, z-value, and percentage agreement with detailed error handling
calculate_kappa_detailed <- function(data, column_gpt, column_olmo) {
  # Ensure both columns exist
  if(column_gpt %in% colnames(data) & column_olmo %in% colnames(data)) {
    # Extract columns
    gpt_col <- data[[column_gpt]]
    olmo_col <- data[[column_olmo]]
    
    # Check if all data in columns are NA
    if (all(is.na(gpt_col)) || all(is.na(olmo_col))) {
      return(c(NA, NA, NA, NA))
    }
    
    # Remove rows with NA values
    valid_data <- data[!is.na(gpt_col) & !is.na(olmo_col), ]
    
    # Calculate Cohen's Kappa using 'kappa2' from the 'irr' package
    kappa_result <- irr::kappa2(data.frame(valid_data[[column_gpt]], valid_data[[column_olmo]]), "unweighted")
    
    # Extract kappa value and p-value
    kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
    p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
    agreement_percentage <- mean(valid_data[[column_gpt]] == valid_data[[column_olmo]]) * 100
    
    # Calculate expected agreement (p_e)
    agreement_table <- table(valid_data[[column_gpt]], valid_data[[column_olmo]])
    n <- sum(agreement_table)  # Total number of pairs
    p_e <- sum(rowSums(agreement_table) * colSums(agreement_table)) / (n^2)
    
    # Calculate observed agreement (p_0)
    p_0 <- agreement_percentage / 100
    
    # Calculate standard error (SE) and z-value if p_e < 1
    if (p_e == 1) {
      se_kappa <- NA
      z_value <- NA
    } else {
      se_kappa <- sqrt((p_0 * (1 - p_0)) / (n * (1 - p_e)^2))
      z_value <- kappa_value / se_kappa
    }
    
    return(c(kappa_value, p_value, z_value, agreement_percentage))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA, NA, NA))
  }
}

# Get all columns with _gpt and _olmo suffixes
gpt_columns_v3 <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_v3 <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_v3)

# Create a dataframe to store the results
kappa_results_v3 <- data.frame(Variable = gpt_columns_v3, Kappa = NA, P_Value = NA, Z_Value = NA, Percent_Agreement = NA)

# Loop over all _gpt and _olmo column pairs and calculate statistics
for(i in 1:length(gpt_columns_v3)) {
  kappa_stats <- calculate_kappa_detailed(data_gpt_olmo_processed, gpt_columns_v3[i], olmo_columns_v3[i])
  kappa_results_v3[i, 2:5] <- kappa_stats
}

# berprfen, ob die Spalte "Kappa" im Datensatz kappa_results existiert
if("Kappa" %in% colnames(kappa_results)) {
  # Berechne den Durchschnitt der Spalte Kappa und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  Average_Kappa_over_categories <- round(mean(kappa_results$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Berechne die Standardabweichung der Spalte Kappa und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  SD_Kappa_over_categories <- round(sd(kappa_results$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Berechne den Bereich der Spalte Kappa und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  Range_Kappa_over_categories <- round(range(kappa_results$Kappa, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Ausgabe der Ergebnisse
  cat("Durchschnittlicher Kappa-Wert ber alle Kategorien:", Average_Kappa_over_categories, "\n")
  cat("Standardabweichung des Kappa-Werts ber alle Kategorien:", SD_Kappa_over_categories, "\n")
  cat("Bereich des Kappa-Werts ber alle Kategorien:", Range_Kappa_over_categories[1], "-", Range_Kappa_over_categories[2], "\n")
} else {
  stop("Die Spalte 'Kappa' existiert nicht im Datensatz kappa_results!")
}

Kappa interrater gpt zu olmo per category 4. ansatz inkl sensitivity,specifity precision per item

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo suffix finden
gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_per_item_v4)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden _olmo-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- gpt_columns_per_item_v4[olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- olmo_columns_per_item_v4[olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Entfernen der Variablen pre_dcp_1_text_gpt und pap_dcp_1_text_gpt, da diese nummerisch sind...
excluded_items <- c("pre_dcp_1_text_gpt", "pap_dcp_1_text_gpt")
valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[!valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 %in% excluded_items]
valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4[!valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", excluded_items)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

# Erstelle einen DataFrame, um die Ergebnisse fr jede Spalte zu speichern
kappa_results_per_item_v4 <- data.frame(Item = character(),
                                        Kappa = numeric(),
                                        P_Value = numeric(),
                                        Z_Value = numeric(),
                                        Percent_Agreement = numeric(),
                                        Sensitivity_n = numeric(),
                                        Specificity_n = numeric(),
                                        Precision_n = numeric(),
                                        stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Berechnung fr jede Spalte einzeln
for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4)) {
  gpt_column_per_item_v4 <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[i]]]
  olmo_column_per_item_v4 <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4[i]]]
  
  # Kombiniere GPT und OLMO Spalten fr den Vergleich
  combined_data_per_item_v4 <- data.frame(GPT = gpt_column_per_item_v4,
                                          OLMO = olmo_column_per_item_v4)

  # Entferne NA-Werte
  combined_data_per_item_v4 <- na.omit(combined_data_per_item_v4)
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa
  kappa_result_per_item_v4 <- irr::kappa2(combined_data_per_item_v4, "unweighted")
  
  # Berechne den Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung
  percent_agreement_per_item_v4 <- sum(combined_data_per_item_v4$GPT == combined_data_per_item_v4$OLMO) / nrow(combined_data_per_item_v4) * 100
  
  # Berechnung der Confusion Matrix (y, n, x Kategorien)
  confusion_matrix <- table(combined_data_per_item_v4$GPT, combined_data_per_item_v4$OLMO)
  
  # Sicherstellen, dass "n" in der Matrix vorhanden ist
  if("n" %in% rownames(confusion_matrix) && "n" %in% colnames(confusion_matrix)) {
    TN <- confusion_matrix["n", "n"]
  } else {
    TN <- 0
  }

  # Berechne False Positives (FP) und False Negatives (FN) fr "n"
  FP <- if("n" %in% rownames(confusion_matrix)) sum(confusion_matrix["n", ]) - TN else 0
  FN <- if("n" %in% colnames(confusion_matrix)) sum(confusion_matrix[, "n"]) - TN else 0
  
  # Berechne True Positives (TP) als restliche bereinstimmungen
  TP <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TN + FP + FN)

  # Berechne Sensitivity (n), Specificity (n) und Precision (n)
  sensitivity_n <- if((TN + FN) > 0) TN / (TN + FN) else NA
  specificity_n <- if((TP + FP) > 0) TP / (TP + FP) else NA
  precision_n <- if((TP + FN) > 0) TP / (TP + FN) else NA
  
  # Ergebnisse in den DataFrame hinzufgen
  kappa_results_per_item_v4 <- rbind(kappa_results_per_item_v4, data.frame(Item = valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[i],
                                                                           Kappa = kappa_result_per_item_v4$value,
                                                                           P_Value = kappa_result_per_item_v4$p.value,
                                                                           Z_Value = kappa_result_per_item_v4$statistic,
                                                                           Percent_Agreement = percent_agreement_per_item_v4,
                                                                           Sensitivity_n = sensitivity_n,
                                                                           Specificity_n = specificity_n,
                                                                           Precision_n = precision_n))
}
## Warning in sqrt(varkappa): NaNs wurden erzeugt
## Warning in sqrt(varkappa): NaNs wurden erzeugt
# Ergebnisse anzeigen
print(kappa_results_per_item_v4)

##gwets ac1

GWETs AC1 per item

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo suffix finden
gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_per_item_v4)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden _olmo-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- gpt_columns_per_item_v4[olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- olmo_columns_per_item_v4[olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Entfernen der Variablen pre_dcp_1_text_gpt und pap_dcp_1_text_gpt, da diese nummerisch sind
excluded_items <- c("pre_dcp_1_text_gpt", "pap_dcp_1_text_gpt")
valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 <- valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[!valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4 %in% excluded_items]
valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 <- valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4[!valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4 %in% gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", excluded_items)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

# Erstelle einen DataFrame, um die Ergebnisse fr jede Spalte zu speichern
ac1_results_per_item_v4 <- data.frame(Item = character(),
                                      AC1 = numeric(),
                                      Percent_Agreement = numeric(),
                                      Sensitivity_n = numeric(),
                                      Specificity_n = numeric(),
                                      Precision_n = numeric(),
                                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Berechnung fr jede Spalte einzeln
for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4)) {
  gpt_column_per_item_v4 <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[i]]]
  olmo_column_per_item_v4 <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_olmo_columns_per_item_v4[i]]]
  
  # Kombiniere GPT und OLMO Spalten fr den Vergleich
  combined_data_per_item_v4 <- data.frame(GPT = gpt_column_per_item_v4,
                                          OLMO = olmo_column_per_item_v4)

  # Entferne NA-Werte
  combined_data_per_item_v4 <- na.omit(combined_data_per_item_v4)
  
  # Erstelle die Hufigkeitstabelle fr GWET's AC1
  agreement_table <- table(combined_data_per_item_v4$GPT, combined_data_per_item_v4$OLMO)

  # Berechne GWET's AC1
  ac1_result_per_item_v4 <- gwet.ac1.raw(agreement_table)

  # Berechne den Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung
  percent_agreement_per_item_v4 <- sum(combined_data_per_item_v4$GPT == combined_data_per_item_v4$OLMO) / nrow(combined_data_per_item_v4) * 100
  
  # Berechnung der Confusion Matrix (y, n, x Kategorien)
  confusion_matrix <- table(combined_data_per_item_v4$GPT, combined_data_per_item_v4$OLMO)
  
  # Sicherstellen, dass "n" in der Matrix vorhanden ist
  if("n" %in% rownames(confusion_matrix) && "n" %in% colnames(confusion_matrix)) {
    TN <- confusion_matrix["n", "n"]
  } else {
    TN <- 0
  }

  # Berechne False Positives (FP) und False Negatives (FN) fr "n"
  FP <- if("n" %in% rownames(confusion_matrix)) sum(confusion_matrix["n", ]) - TN else 0
  FN <- if("n" %in% colnames(confusion_matrix)) sum(confusion_matrix[, "n"]) - TN else 0
  
  # Berechne True Positives (TP) als restliche bereinstimmungen
  TP <- sum(confusion_matrix) - (TN + FP + FN)

  # Berechne Sensitivity (n), Specificity (n) und Precision (n)
  sensitivity_n <- if((TN + FN) > 0) TN / (TN + FN) else NA
  specificity_n <- if((TP + FP) > 0) TP / (TP + FP) else NA
  precision_n <- if((TP + FN) > 0) TP / (TP + FN) else NA
  
  # Ergebnisse in den DataFrame hinzufgen
  ac1_results_per_item_v4 <- rbind(ac1_results_per_item_v4, data.frame(Item = valid_gpt_columns_per_item_v4[i],
                                                                        AC1 = ac1_result_per_item_v4$est,
                                                                        Percent_Agreement = percent_agreement_per_item_v4,
                                                                        Sensitivity_n = sensitivity_n,
                                                                        Specificity_n = specificity_n,
                                                                        Precision_n = precision_n))
}

# Ergebnisse anzeigen
print(ac1_results_per_item_v4)

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo suffix finden
gpt_columns <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden _olmo-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns <- gpt_columns[olmo_columns %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns <- olmo_columns[olmo_columns %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Entfernen der Variablen pre_dcp_1_text_gpt und pap_dcp_1_text_gpt, da diese nummerisch sind
excluded_items <- c("pre_dcp_1_text_gpt", "pap_dcp_1_text_gpt")
valid_gpt_columns <- valid_gpt_columns[!valid_gpt_columns %in% excluded_items]
valid_olmo_columns <- valid_olmo_columns[!valid_olmo_columns %in% gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", excluded_items)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

# Kombiniere alle gltigen GPT und OLMO Spalten in eine lange Liste
all_gpt_values <- unlist(data_gpt_olmo_processed[valid_gpt_columns])
all_olmo_values <- unlist(data_gpt_olmo_processed[valid_olmo_columns])

# Sicherstellen, dass die Kategorien konsistent sind (3 Kategorien z.B. Y, N, X)
# Umwandlung in Faktoren, falls die Werte nicht schon Faktoren sind
all_gpt_values <- factor(all_gpt_values, levels = c("Y", "N", "X"))
all_olmo_values <- factor(all_olmo_values, levels = c("Y", "N", "X"))

# Erstelle eine Hufigkeitstabelle fr GWET's AC1
combined_data <- data.frame(GPT = all_gpt_values, OLMO = all_olmo_values)
combined_data <- na.omit(combined_data)
agreement_table <- table(combined_data$GPT, combined_data$OLMO)

# Berechne GWET's AC1 ber alle Items
ac1_overall <- gwet.ac1.raw(agreement_table)

# Extrahiere den Schtzwert und zeige das Ergebnis an
cat("GWET's AC1 ber alle Items:", ac1_overall$est$coeff.val, "\n")
## GWET's AC1 ber alle Items: 1
# Vollstndiges Ergebnis von GWET's AC1 anzeigen
print(ac1_overall)

gpt /olmo interrater nur comparison/nur extraction prompt (gesamtdatenset)

# Funktion zur Berechnung des 95%-Konfidenzintervalls fr Cohen's Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, se_kappa) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa)) {
    ci_lower <- kappa_value - 1.96 * se_kappa
    ci_upper <- kappa_value + 1.96 * se_kappa
    return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein CI, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Extrahiere die GPT und OLMO Spalten fr beide Vergleiche (Extraction und Comparison)
gpt_columns_extract <- grep("^(c_pre|pre|c_pap|pap).*_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_extract <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_extract)

gpt_columns_comp <- grep("^(c_match|match).*_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_comp <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_comp)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden OLMO-Spalten existieren (fr beide Gruppen)
valid_gpt_columns_extract <- gpt_columns_extract[olmo_columns_extract %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_extract <- olmo_columns_extract[olmo_columns_extract %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

valid_gpt_columns_comp <- gpt_columns_comp[olmo_columns_comp %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_comp <- olmo_columns_comp[olmo_columns_comp %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

if(length(valid_gpt_columns_extract) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten fr Extraction gefunden!")
}
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_comp) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten fr Comparison gefunden!")
}

# Daten fr beide Vergleiche kombinieren und NA-Werte entfernen

combined_data_comp <- data.frame()

                                                             OLMO = data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_olmo_columns_comp[i]]]))

  z_value_extract <- NA
} else {

# Funktion zur Berechnung des 95%-Konfidenzintervalls fr Cohen's Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, se_kappa) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa)) {
    ci_lower <- kappa_value - 1.96 * se_kappa
    ci_upper <- kappa_value + 1.96 * se_kappa
    return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein CI, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo Suffix finden
gpt_columns <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns)

valid_gpt_columns <- gpt_columns[olmo_columns %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns <- olmo_columns[olmo_columns %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

if(length(valid_gpt_columns) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

combined_data <- data.frame()

for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns)) {
  # Fge die Werte der GPT und OLMO Spalten zur kombinierten Datensatz hinzu
  combined_data <- rbind(combined_data, data.frame(GPT = data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_gpt_columns[i]]],
                                                   OLMO = data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_olmo_columns[i]]]))
}

# Entferne NA-Werte
combined_data <- na.omit(combined_data)

n_total <- nrow(combined_data)  # Anzahl der Vergleiche

# Berechne den Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung

##       ist kein Vielfaches der Lnge des krzeren Objektes

if (p_e == 1) {
  se_kappa <- NA
  z_value <- NA

  z_value <- kappa_result$value / se_kappa
}

# Funktion zur Berechnung des 95%-Konfidenzintervalls fr Cohen's Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, se_kappa) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa)) {
    ci_lower <- kappa_value - 1.96 * se_kappa
    ci_upper <- kappa_value + 1.96 * se_kappa
    return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein CI, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo Suffix finden
gpt_columns_PromptV <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_PromptV <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_PromptV)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden _olmo-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns_PromptV <- gpt_columns_PromptV[olmo_columns_PromptV %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_PromptV <- olmo_columns_PromptV[olmo_columns_PromptV %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_PromptV) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

# Definiere die verschiedenen Versionen, die in prompt_version auftreten (A, B, C, D)
versions_PromptV <- c("A", "B", "C", "D")

# Schleife durch jede Version und berechne das Kappa fr jede
for (version_PromptV in versions_PromptV) {
  # Filtere die Zeilen, die zur aktuellen Version gehren
  version_data_PromptV <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[data_gpt_olmo_processed$prompt_version == version_PromptV, ]
  
  # Kombinieren der Spalten in einem DataFrame fr den Vergleich der aktuellen Version
  combined_data_PromptV <- data.frame()
  
  for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_PromptV)) {
    # Fge die Werte der GPT und OLMO Spalten zur kombinierten Datensatz hinzu
    combined_data_PromptV <- rbind(combined_data_PromptV, data.frame(GPT = version_data_PromptV[[valid_gpt_columns_PromptV[i]]],
                                                                     OLMO = version_data_PromptV[[valid_olmo_columns_PromptV[i]]]))
  }
  
  # Entferne NA-Werte
  combined_data_PromptV <- na.omit(combined_data_PromptV)
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa fr die aktuelle Version
  kappa_result_PromptV <- irr::kappa2(combined_data_PromptV, "unweighted")
  n_PromptV <- nrow(combined_data_PromptV)  # Anzahl der Vergleiche
  
  # Berechne den Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung
  percent_agreement_PromptV <- sum(combined_data_PromptV$GPT == combined_data_PromptV$OLMO) / n_PromptV * 100
  
  # Berechnung des Standardfehlers
  p_e_PromptV <- sum(rowSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO)) * colSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO))) / (n_PromptV^2)
  p_0_PromptV <- percent_agreement_PromptV / 100
  
  if (p_e_PromptV == 1) {
    se_kappa_PromptV <- NA
    z_value_PromptV <- NA
  } else {
    se_kappa_PromptV <- sqrt((p_0_PromptV * (1 - p_0_PromptV)) / (n_PromptV * (1 - p_e_PromptV)^2))
    z_value_PromptV <- kappa_result_PromptV$value / se_kappa_PromptV
  }
  
  # Berechne das 95%-Konfidenzintervall fr Kappa
  ci_kappa_PromptV <- calculate_kappa_confidence_interval(kappa_result_PromptV$value, se_kappa_PromptV)
  
  # Ergebnisse anzeigen
  cat("\nCohen's Kappa fr Version", version_PromptV, ":\n")
  cat("Kappa:", kappa_result_PromptV$value, "\n")
  cat("95%-Konfidenzintervall:", sprintf("[%.3f, %.3f]", ci_kappa_PromptV[1], ci_kappa_PromptV[2]), "\n")
  cat("p-Wert:", kappa_result_PromptV$p.value, "\n")
  cat("z-Wert:", z_value_PromptV, "\n")

  cat("Anzahl der Vergleiche (n):", n_PromptV, "\n")
}

siginifikanztest unterscheid promptversion a zu d

# Funktion zur Berechnung des Fisher-Z-Werts fr den Unterschied zwischen zwei Kappa-Werten
calculate_z_difference <- function(kappa1, se_kappa1, kappa2, se_kappa2) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa1) & !is.na(se_kappa2)) {
    z_diff <- (kappa1 - kappa2) / sqrt(se_kappa1^2 + se_kappa2^2)
    p_value <- 2 * (1 - pnorm(abs(z_diff)))  # zweiseitiger Test
    return(c(z_diff, p_value))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein Vergleich mglich, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Definiere die Versionen A und D fr den Vergleich
version_compare <- c("A", "D")

# Speichern der Kappa-Ergebnisse fr A und D
kappa_results_z <- list()

for (version_PromptV in version_compare) {
  # Filtere die Zeilen fr die aktuelle Version
  version_data_PromptV <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[data_gpt_olmo_processed$prompt_version == version_PromptV, ]
  
  combined_data_PromptV <- data.frame()
  
  for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_PromptV)) {
    combined_data_PromptV <- rbind(combined_data_PromptV, data.frame(GPT = version_data_PromptV[[valid_gpt_columns_PromptV[i]]],
                                                                     OLMO = version_data_PromptV[[valid_olmo_columns_PromptV[i]]]))
  }
  
  combined_data_PromptV <- na.omit(combined_data_PromptV)
  
  kappa_result_PromptV <- irr::kappa2(combined_data_PromptV, "unweighted")
  n_PromptV <- nrow(combined_data_PromptV)
  
  p_e_PromptV <- sum(rowSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO)) * colSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO))) / (n_PromptV^2)
  p_0_PromptV <- sum(combined_data_PromptV$GPT == combined_data_PromptV$OLMO) / n_PromptV
  
  if (p_e_PromptV == 1) {
    se_kappa_PromptV <- NA
  } else {
    se_kappa_PromptV <- sqrt((p_0_PromptV * (1 - p_0_PromptV)) / (n_PromptV * (1 - p_e_PromptV)^2))
  }
  
  # Speichern der Kappa-Werte und Standardfehler fr Vergleich
  kappa_results_z[[version_PromptV]] <- list(kappa = kappa_result_PromptV$value, se = se_kappa_PromptV)
}
## Warning in rowSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO)) * : Lnge des lngeren Objektes
##       ist kein Vielfaches der Lnge des krzeren Objektes
## Warning in rowSums(table(combined_data_PromptV$GPT, combined_data_PromptV$OLMO)) * : Lnge des lngeren Objektes
##       ist kein Vielfaches der Lnge des krzeren Objektes
# Berechnen des Z-Werts und p-Werts fr den Unterschied zwischen A und D
z_diff_results <- calculate_z_difference(kappa_results_z[["A"]]$kappa, kappa_results_z[["A"]]$se,
                                         kappa_results_z[["D"]]$kappa, kappa_results_z[["D"]]$se)

cat("\nUnterschied zwischen Cohen's Kappa fr Version A und D:\n")
## 
## Unterschied zwischen Cohen's Kappa fr Version A und D:
cat("Z-Wert:", z_diff_results[1], "\n")
## Z-Wert: -5.811836
cat("p-Wert:", z_diff_results[2], "\n")
## p-Wert: 6.179123e-09

###signifikanztest unterschied extraction comparison steigers z

                                         kappa_result_comp$value, se_kappa_comp)

cat("\nUnterschied zwischen Kappa fr Extraction und Comparison:\n")
## 
## Unterschied zwischen Kappa fr Extraction und Comparison:
cat("Z-Wert:", z_diff_results[1], "\n")
## Z-Wert: 4.257885
cat("p-Wert:", z_diff_results[2], "\n")

interrater Kappa NUR Y & N

interrater kappa y_n all categories

# Function to calculate Cohen's Kappa, p-value, z-value, percentage agreement, and number of comparisons using 'irr' package
calculate_kappa_irr_filtered_debug <- function(data, column_gpt, column_olmo) {
  # Ensure both columns exist
  if (column_gpt %in% colnames(data) & column_olmo %in% colnames(data)) {
    # Filter rows where the OLMO column is either "Y" or "N"
    valid_data <- data[data[[column_olmo]] %in% c("y", "n"), ]
    
    # Debug: Print number of valid rows for the comparison
    print(paste("Number of valid rows for comparison (", column_gpt, " & ", column_olmo, "): ", nrow(valid_data)))
    
    # Check if there are any valid rows left for comparison
    if (nrow(valid_data) > 0) {
      # Remove rows with NA values in the selected columns
      valid_data <- valid_data[!is.na(valid_data[[column_gpt]]) & !is.na(valid_data[[column_olmo]]), ]
      
      # Debug: Print number of rows after removing NAs
      print(paste("Number of valid rows after removing NAs: ", nrow(valid_data)))
      
      # Check again if there are rows left after removing NAs
      if (nrow(valid_data) > 0) {
        # Calculate Cohen's Kappa using the 'kappa2' function from the irr package
        kappa_result <- irr::kappa2(valid_data[, c(column_gpt, column_olmo)], "unweighted")
        
        # Extract values
        kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
        p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
        z_value <- kappa_result$statistic
        percent_agreement <- sum(valid_data[[column_gpt]] == valid_data[[column_olmo]]) / nrow(valid_data) * 100
        
        # Return the results including the number of comparisons (N)
        return(c(kappa_value, p_value, z_value, percent_agreement, nrow(valid_data)))
      } else {
        # No valid comparisons available after NA removal
        print("No valid rows left after removing NAs.")
        return(rep(NA, 5))
      }
    } else {
      # No valid comparisons based on OLMO filter
      print("No valid rows based on OLMO filter (Y/N).")
      return(rep(NA, 5))
    }
  } else {
    print(paste("Columns", column_gpt, "or", column_olmo, "do not exist in the dataset."))
    return(rep(NA, 5))
  }
}

# Get all columns that have _gpt or _olmo suffix
gpt_columns <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns)

# Create a dataframe to store the results
kappa_results_filtered_debug <- data.frame(
  Variable = gpt_columns,
  Kappa = NA,
  P_Value = NA,
  Z_Value = NA,
  Percent_Agreement = NA,
  N_Comparisons = NA
)

# Loop over all _gpt and _olmo column pairs and calculate statistics
for (i in 1:length(gpt_columns)) {
  print(paste("Processing columns:", gpt_columns[i], "and", olmo_columns[i]))
  kappa_stats_filtered_debug <- calculate_kappa_irr_filtered_debug(data_gpt_olmo_processed, gpt_columns[i], olmo_columns[i])
  kappa_results_filtered_debug[i, 2:6] <- kappa_stats_filtered_debug
}

# Funktion zur Berechnung des 95%-Konfidenzintervalls fr Cohen's Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, se_kappa) {
  if (!is.na(se_kappa)) {
    ci_lower <- kappa_value - 1.96 * se_kappa
    ci_upper <- kappa_value + 1.96 * se_kappa
    return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
  } else {
    return(c(NA, NA))  # Kein CI, falls SE nicht berechnet werden kann
  }
}

# Funktion zur Berechnung des Standardfehlers und der erwarteten bereinstimmung
calculate_standard_error <- function(data) {
  # Erstelle die Kontingenztabelle
  contingency_table <- table(data$GPT, data$OLMO)
  
  # Berechne die Zeilen- und Spaltensummen der Kontingenztabelle
  row_sums <- rowSums(contingency_table)
  col_sums <- colSums(contingency_table)
  
  # Anzahl der Paare
  n <- sum(contingency_table)
  
  # Berechnung der erwarteten bereinstimmung (p_e)
  p_e <- sum(row_sums * col_sums) / (n^2)
  
  # Berechne den beobachteten Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung (p_0)
  percent_agreement <- sum(diag(contingency_table)) / n * 100
  p_0 <- percent_agreement / 100
  
  return(list(p_e = p_e, p_0 = p_0, n = n))
}

# Funktion zur Berechnung von Cohen's Kappa, p-Wert, z-Wert, prozentuale bereinstimmung, Anzahl der Vergleiche und Konfidenzintervall
calculate_overall_kappa <- function(data, gpt_columns, olmo_columns) {
  # Erstelle einen leeren DataFrame fr die relevanten Vergleichswerte
  combined_data <- data.frame(GPT = character(), OLMO = character(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  
  # Schleife ber alle GPT und OLMO Spalten, um gltige Zeilen zu sammeln
  for (i in 1:length(gpt_columns)) {
    if (gpt_columns[i] %in% colnames(data) & olmo_columns[i] %in% colnames(data)) {
      # Filtere nur Zeilen, in denen der OLMO-Wert "y" oder "n" ist
      valid_rows <- data[data[[olmo_columns[i]]] %in% c("y", "n"), ]
      
      # Whle die relevanten GPT- und OLMO-Werte aus und entferne NA-Werte
      valid_rows <- valid_rows[!is.na(valid_rows[[gpt_columns[i]]]) & !is.na(valid_rows[[olmo_columns[i]]]), ]
      
      # Fge die gltigen GPT- und OLMO-Werte in den kombinierten DataFrame ein
      combined_data <- rbind(combined_data, data.frame(GPT = valid_rows[[gpt_columns[i]]], OLMO = valid_rows[[olmo_columns[i]]]))
    }
  }
  
  # berprfe, ob gengend Datenpunkte vorhanden sind, um Kappa zu berechnen
  if (nrow(combined_data) > 0) {
    # Berechne Cohen's Kappa ber alle kombinierten Zellen
    kappa_result <- irr::kappa2(combined_data, "unweighted")
    
    # Extrahiere Kappa-Wert, p-Wert und z-Wert
    kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
    p_value <- kappa_result$p.value
    z_value <- kappa_result$statistic
    percent_agreement <- sum(combined_data$GPT == combined_data$OLMO) / nrow(combined_data) * 100
    n_comparisons <- nrow(combined_data)
    
    # Berechne den Standardfehler und die erwartete bereinstimmung
    agreement_info <- calculate_standard_error(combined_data)
    p_e <- agreement_info$p_e
    p_0 <- agreement_info$p_0
    
    # Berechne den Standardfehler
    if (p_e == 1) {
      se_kappa <- NA
    } else {
      se_kappa <- sqrt((p_0 * (1 - p_0)) / (n_comparisons * (1 - p_e)^2))
    }
    
    # Berechne das 95%-Konfidenzintervall fr Kappa
    ci_kappa <- calculate_kappa_confidence_interval(kappa_value, se_kappa)
    
    # Rckgabe der Ergebnisse einschlielich des Konfidenzintervalls
    return(data.frame(Kappa_Gesamt = kappa_value, P_Value = p_value, Z_Value = z_value, Percent_Agreement = percent_agreement, 
                      N_Comparisons = n_comparisons, CI_Lower = ci_kappa[1], CI_Upper = ci_kappa[2]))
  } else {
    # Rckgabe von NA, wenn keine gltigen Vergleiche vorhanden sind
    return(data.frame(Kappa_Gesamt = NA, P_Value = NA, Z_Value = NA, Percent_Agreement = NA, N_Comparisons = 0, CI_Lower = NA, CI_Upper = NA))
  }
}

# Definiere die zu vergleichenden Variablenpaare
variables_to_compare_ve <- c("match_dv_0", "match_dv_1", "match_dv_2", "match_dv_3",
                             "match_dcp_1", "match_dcp_2", "match_sm_1", "match_sm_2", "match_sm_3")

# Liste zur Speicherung der Ergebnisse
results_ve <- data.frame(Variable_ve = character(), 
                         Kappa_ve = numeric(), 
                         N_ve = numeric(),
                         Agreement_Percent_ve = numeric(),
                         CI_Lower_ve = numeric(),  # Konfidenzintervall untere Grenze
                         CI_Upper_ve = numeric(),  # Konfidenzintervall obere Grenze
                         Accuracy_ve = numeric(),
                         Sensitivity_ve = numeric(),
                         Specificity_ve = numeric(),
                         N_Count_Olmo = numeric(),
                         N_Count_GPT = numeric(),
                         Y_Count_Olmo = numeric(),
                         Y_Count_GPT = numeric(),
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Berechnung von Cohen's Kappa und weiteren Kennzahlen fr jede Variable
for (variable in variables_to_compare_ve) {
  # Definiere die Spaltennamen fr GPT und Olmo
  gpt_column <- paste0(variable, "_gpt")
  olmo_column <- paste0(variable, "_olmo")
  
  # Selektiere die relevanten Spalten und entferne Zeilen mit NA-Werten nur in diesen Spalten
  comparison_data <- data_gpt_ve_filtered %>%
    select(gpt_column, olmo_column) %>%
    filter(!is.na(.[[gpt_column]]) & !is.na(.[[olmo_column]]))
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa fr die aktuelle Variable
  kappa_obj_ve <- kappa2(comparison_data)
  kappa_value_ve <- kappa_obj_ve$value
  
  # Anzahl der Vergleiche (N)
  n_comparisons_ve <- nrow(comparison_data)
  
  # Berechne den prozentualen Anteil der bereinstimmungen
  agreement_percent_ve <- mean(comparison_data[[gpt_column]] == comparison_data[[olmo_column]]) * 100

  # Berechne den Standardfehler fr Cohen's Kappa
  se_kappa_ve <- sqrt((1 - kappa_value_ve^2) / n_comparisons_ve)
  
  # Berechne das 95%-Konfidenzintervall (z-Wert von 1.96 fr 95%)
  ci_lower_ve <- kappa_value_ve - 1.96 * se_kappa_ve
  ci_upper_ve <- kappa_value_ve + 1.96 * se_kappa_ve
  
  # Erstelle Confusion-Matrix
  confusion_matrix <- table(comparison_data[[gpt_column]], comparison_data[[olmo_column]])
  true_positive <- confusion_matrix[2, 2]
  true_negative <- confusion_matrix[1, 1]
  false_positive <- confusion_matrix[1, 2]
  false_negative <- confusion_matrix[2, 1]

  # Berechne Genauigkeit, Spezifitt und Sensitivitt
  accuracy_ve <- (true_positive + true_negative) / n_comparisons_ve
  sensitivity_ve <- true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative)
  specificity_ve <- true_negative / (true_negative + false_positive)
  
  # Zhle die Anzahl der "N"- und "Y"-Werte in den Spalten von GPT und Olmo
  n_count_olmo <- sum(comparison_data[[olmo_column]] == "n", na.rm = TRUE)
  n_count_gpt <- sum(comparison_data[[gpt_column]] == "n", na.rm = TRUE)
  y_count_olmo <- sum(comparison_data[[olmo_column]] == "y", na.rm = TRUE)
  y_count_gpt <- sum(comparison_data[[gpt_column]] == "y", na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Ergebnisse speichern mit den Endungen _ve
  results_ve <- rbind(results_ve, data.frame(Variable_ve = variable, 
                                             Kappa_ve = kappa_value_ve, 
                                             N_ve = n_comparisons_ve,
                                             Agreement_Percent_ve = agreement_percent_ve,
                                             CI_Lower_ve = ci_lower_ve,  
                                             CI_Upper_ve = ci_upper_ve,
                                             Accuracy_ve = accuracy_ve,
                                             Sensitivity_ve = sensitivity_ve,
                                             Specificity_ve = specificity_ve,
                                             N_Count_Olmo = n_count_olmo,
                                             N_Count_GPT = n_count_gpt,
                                             Y_Count_Olmo = y_count_olmo,
                                             Y_Count_GPT = y_count_gpt))
}

Interrater kappa ve total

# Funktion zur Berechnung des Konfidenzintervalls fr Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, n, alpha = 0.05) {
  # Standardfehler von Kappa
  standard_error <- sqrt((1 - kappa_value^2) / n)
  
  # Z-Wert fr das gewnschte Konfidenzniveau (z.B. 95%)
  z_value <- qnorm(1 - alpha / 2)
  
  # Berechnung der unteren und oberen Grenze des Konfidenzintervalls
  ci_lower <- kappa_value - z_value * standard_error
  ci_upper <- kappa_value + z_value * standard_error
  
  return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
}

                                     stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

  # Definiere die Spaltennamen fr GPT und Olmo
  gpt_column <- paste0(variable, "_gpt")
  olmo_column <- paste0(variable, "_olmo")
  
  # Selektiere die relevanten Spalten und entferne Zeilen mit NA-Werten nur in diesen Spalten
  comparison_data <- data_gpt_ve_total_filtered %>%
    select(gpt_column, olmo_column) %>%
    filter(!is.na(.[[gpt_column]]) & !is.na(.[[olmo_column]])) %>%
    rename(GPT_Rating_ve_total = gpt_column, Olmo_Rating_ve_total = olmo_column)
  
  # Fge die gefilterten Daten zum kombinierten Datensatz hinzu

# Step 1: Filter the dataset into test and retest subsets
test_data_ve <- data_gpt_ve_filtered %>% filter(test_retest == "Test")
retest_data_ve <- data_gpt_ve_filtered %>% filter(test_retest == "RETEST")

# Step 2: Match test and retest based on 'psp' (this will contain only the  test-retest psp rows)
retest_merged_data_ve <- merge(test_data_ve, retest_data_ve, by = "psp", suffixes = c("_test_ve", "_retest_ve"))

# Step 3: Get all columns ending with '-gpt' or '_gpt'
comp_columns_ve <- grep("[-_]gpt$", names(data_gpt_ve_filtered), value = TRUE)

# Step 4: Loop through each 'gpt' column and calculate Cohen's Kappa using the irr package
retest_kappa_results_ve <- lapply(comp_columns_ve, function(col_name) {
  # Cohen's Kappa requires the two sets of categorical data (Test and RETEST)
  test_col_ve <- retest_merged_data_ve[[paste0(col_name, "_test_ve")]]
  retest_col_ve <- retest_merged_data_ve[[paste0(col_name, "_retest_ve")]]
  
  # berprfung auf gltige Daten (Nicht-NA-Daten) in beiden Spalten
  if (all(is.na(test_col_ve)) || all(is.na(retest_col_ve))) {
    # Falls alle Daten NA sind, gib eine Zeile mit NA zurck
    return(data.frame(Column = col_name, Kappa = NA, z_value = NA, 
                      Agreement_Percentage = NA, p_value = NA))
  }
  
  # Berechnung von Cohen's Kappa mit dem irr-Paket
  kappa_result_ve <- kappa2(data.frame(test_col_ve, retest_col_ve), weight = "unweighted")
  
  # Extrahiere den Kappa-Wert und p-Wert
  kappa_value_ve <- kappa_result_ve$value
  p_value_ve <- kappa_result_ve$p.value
  agreement_percentage_ve <- mean(test_col_ve == retest_col_ve, na.rm = TRUE) * 100
  
  # Berechnung der erwarteten bereinstimmung (p_e)
  test_table_ve <- table(test_col_ve, retest_col_ve)
  n_ve <- sum(test_table_ve)  # Anzahl der Paare
  p_e_ve <- sum(rowSums(test_table_ve) * colSums(test_table_ve)) / (n_ve^2)
  
  # Berechnung der beobachteten bereinstimmung (p_0)
  p_0_ve <- agreement_percentage_ve / 100
  
  # Berechnung des Standardfehlers (SE)
  if (p_e_ve == 1) {
    se_kappa_ve <- NA  # Vermeide Division durch 0, wenn p_e = 1 (perfekte bereinstimmung)
    z_value_ve <- NA
  } else {
    se_kappa_ve <- sqrt((p_0_ve * (1 - p_0_ve)) / (n_ve * (1 - p_e_ve)^2))
  
    # Berechnung des z-Werts
    z_value_ve <- kappa_value_ve / se_kappa_ve
  }
  
  # Return the column name, Kappa, z-value, agreement %, and p-value
  return(data.frame(Column = col_name, Kappa = kappa_value_ve, z_value = z_value_ve, 
                    Agreement_Percentage = agreement_percentage_ve, p_value = p_value_ve))
})

# Step 5: Combine the results into a single data frame
retest_kappa_summary_ve <- do.call(rbind, retest_kappa_results_ve)

# Step 6: Display the results
print(retest_kappa_summary_ve)

# Funktion zur Berechnung des Konfidenzintervalls fr Kappa
calculate_kappa_confidence_interval <- function(kappa_value, n, alpha = 0.05) {
  # Standardfehler von Kappa
  standard_error <- sqrt((1 - kappa_value^2) / n)
  
  # Z-Wert fr das gewnschte Konfidenzniveau (z.B. 95%)
  z_value <- qnorm(1 - alpha / 2)
  
  # Berechnung der unteren und oberen Grenze des Konfidenzintervalls
  ci_lower <- kappa_value - z_value * standard_error
  ci_upper <- kappa_value + z_value * standard_error
  
  return(c(ci_lower, ci_upper))
}

# Vergleichs-Spalten fr c_match und match extrahieren
gpt_columns_comp <- grep("^(c_match|match).*_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_comp <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_comp)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden OLMO-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns_comp <- gpt_columns_comp[olmo_columns_comp %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_comp <- olmo_columns_comp[olmo_columns_comp %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_comp) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten fr Comparison gefunden!")
}

# Daten fr Comparison kombinieren und NA-Werte entfernen
combined_data_comp <- data.frame()
for(i in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_comp)) {
  combined_data_comp <- rbind(combined_data_comp, data.frame(GPT = data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_gpt_columns_comp[i]]],
                                                             OLMO = data_gpt_olmo_processed[[valid_olmo_columns_comp[i]]],
                                                             size_kb_sum = data_gpt_olmo_processed$size_kb_sum))
}
combined_data_comp <- na.omit(combined_data_comp)

# Berechne die Terzile basierend auf der Spalte 'size_kb_sum'
tertile_cutoffs <- quantile(combined_data_comp$size_kb_sum, probs = c(1/3, 2/3))

# Einteilung in small, medium und large Terzile
combined_data_comp$tertile <- cut(combined_data_comp$size_kb_sum, 
                                  breaks = c(-Inf, tertile_cutoffs[1], tertile_cutoffs[2], Inf), 
                                  labels = c("small", "medium", "large"))

# Funktion zum Berechnen von Cohen's Kappa fr eine bestimmte Terzile
compute_kappa_for_tertile <- function(data, tertile_label) {
  # Filtere Daten fr das gegebene Terzil
  data_filtered <- subset(data, tertile == tertile_label)
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa
  kappa_result <- irr::kappa2(data_filtered[, c("GPT", "OLMO")], "unweighted")
  kappa_value <- kappa_result$value
  
  # Berechne das Konfidenzintervall
  ci_kappa <- calculate_kappa_confidence_interval(kappa_value, nrow(data_filtered))
  
  # Berechne den Prozentsatz der bereinstimmung
  percent_agreement <- sum(data_filtered$GPT == data_filtered$OLMO) / nrow(data_filtered) * 100
  
  # Ergebnisse runden und anzeigen
  cat("Cohen's Kappa fr", tertile_label, ":\n")
  cat("Kappa:", round(kappa_value, 2), "\n")
  cat("Konfidenzintervall:", round(ci_kappa[1], 2), "-", round(ci_kappa[2], 2), "\n")
  cat("p-Wert:", round(kappa_result$p.value, 2), "\n")
  cat("z-Wert:", round(kappa_result$statistic, 2), "\n")
  cat("Prozentuale bereinstimmung:", round(percent_agreement, 2), "%\n\n")
}

# Spalten mit _gpt und _olmo suffix finden
gpt_columns_peritem <- grep("_gpt$", colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed), value = TRUE)
olmo_columns_peritem <- gsub("_gpt$", "_olmo", gpt_columns_peritem)

# berprfen, ob die entsprechenden _olmo-Spalten existieren
valid_gpt_columns_peritem <- gpt_columns_peritem[olmo_columns_peritem %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]
valid_olmo_columns_peritem <- olmo_columns_peritem[olmo_columns_peritem %in% colnames(data_gpt_olmo_processed)]

# Sicherstellen, dass nur gltige Paare verwendet werden
if(length(valid_gpt_columns_peritem) == 0) {
  stop("Keine gltigen Paare von GPT- und OLMO-Spalten gefunden!")
}

# Berechnung von Kappa pro Zeile basierend auf der Spalte 'psp'
psp_values <- unique(data_gpt_olmo_processed$psp)
results_peritem <- data.frame(psp = psp_values, kappa_value = NA, percent_agreement = NA)

for (i in 1:length(psp_values)) {
  # Filtere die Daten fr die aktuelle Zeile/psp-Nummer
  current_data <- data_gpt_olmo_processed[data_gpt_olmo_processed$psp == psp_values[i], ]
  
  # Kombiniere die Spalten von GPT und OLMO
  combined_data_peritem <- data.frame()
  
  for(j in 1:length(valid_gpt_columns_peritem)) {
    combined_data_peritem <- rbind(combined_data_peritem, data.frame(GPT = current_data[[valid_gpt_columns_peritem[j]]],
                                                                     OLMO = current_data[[valid_olmo_columns_peritem[j]]]))
  }
  
  # Entferne NA-Werte
  combined_data_peritem <- na.omit(combined_data_peritem)
  
  # Berechne Cohen's Kappa pro Zeile/psp
  if (nrow(combined_data_peritem) > 0) {
    kappa_result_peritem <- irr::kappa2(combined_data_peritem, "unweighted")
    percent_agreement_peritem <- sum(combined_data_peritem$GPT == combined_data_peritem$OLMO) / nrow(combined_data_peritem) * 100
    results_peritem$kappa_value[i] <- kappa_result_peritem$value
    results_peritem$percent_agreement[i] <- percent_agreement_peritem
  }
}

# Ergebnisse anzeigen
cat("Kappa pro Zeile (psp):\n")
## Kappa pro Zeile (psp):
print(results_peritem)

## 4    23  0.267995120          50.00000

average over psp

if("kappa_value" %in% colnames(results_peritem)) {
  # Berechne den Durchschnitt der Spalte kappa_value und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  Average_Kappa_over_psp <- round(mean(results_peritem$kappa_value, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Berechne die Standardabweichung der Spalte kappa_value und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  SD_Kappa_over_psp <- round(sd(results_peritem$kappa_value, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Berechne den Bereich der Spalte kappa_value und runde auf 2 Nachkommastellen
  Range_Kappa_over_psp <- round(range(results_peritem$kappa_value, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  
  # Ausgabe der Ergebnisse
  cat("Durchschnittlicher Kappa-Wert ber alle psp:", Average_Kappa_over_psp, "\n")
  cat("Standardabweichung des Kappa-Werts ber alle psp:", SD_Kappa_over_psp, "\n")
  cat("Bereich des Kappa-Werts ber alle psp:", Range_Kappa_over_psp[1], "-", Range_Kappa_over_psp[2], "\n")
} else {
  stop("Die Spalte 'kappa_value' existiert nicht im Datensatz results_peritem!")
}
## Durchschnittlicher Kappa-Wert ber alle psp: 0.31 
## Standardabweichung des Kappa-Werts ber alle psp: 0.15 
## Bereich des Kappa-Werts ber alle psp: -0.09 - 0.79

Overview and analysis per psp

# berblick ber die Kappa-Werte und Prozentbereinstimmung

# Datensatz nach Kappa-Werten sortieren (absteigend)
results_sorted_kappa <- results_peritem[order(-results_peritem$kappa_value), ]

# Datensatz nach Prozentbereinstimmung sortieren (absteigend)
results_sorted_agreement <- results_peritem[order(-results_peritem$percent_agreement), ]

# Kategorisierung der Kappa-Werte (Beispiel: gut >= 0.75, mittel >= 0.4, schlecht < 0.4)
results_peritem$kappa_category <- cut(results_peritem$kappa_value, 
                                      breaks = c(-Inf, 0.4, 0.75, Inf), 
                                      labels = c("schlecht", "mittel", "gut"))

# Zusammenfassung der Kategorien
summary_kappa <- table(results_peritem$kappa_category)

# Ergebnisse anzeigen
cat("Kappa-Kategorien berblick:\n")
## Kappa-Kategorien berblick:
print(summary_kappa)

## schlecht   mittel      gut 
##      194       84        1

boxplot(results_peritem$kappa_value, main = "Verteilung der Kappa-Werte", ylab = "Kappa-Wert")

# Optional: Histogramm der Kappa-Werte
hist(results_peritem$kappa_value, main = "Histogramm der Kappa-Werte", xlab = "Kappa-Wert", breaks = 50)

# Shapiro-Wilk-Test zur berprfung auf Normalverteilung der Kappa-Werte
